All anterior dentition crowding (LII) was measured to the nearest 0.1 mm with a fine-tip digital caliper (Point Digital Calliper SC02, Tresna Instruments, Guilin, China) by the same qualified technician. LII is the sum of the 5 linear distances from one anatomic contact point to the adjacent contact point of the 6 anterior teeth. It has been extensively used to document the degree of anterior tooth crowding, and Bernabé et al. concluded that LII is an accurate and valid method for measuring anterior arch length discrepancy[32–34]. LII measurements were made on initial models (T0) and aligned models (T1). The weekly rate of crowding resolution was calculated as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
